export const lessonTextsEN: Record<number, string> = {
  // Chapter 1 — Start, Calm
  1: "I type calmly. I don't need to rush. Each key is a small step forward. My fingers rest naturally on the home row. The rhythm begins here, in this moment. I notice each letter as it arrives. There is no hurry in this space. I breathe and let my hands find their own way forward.",
  2: "Rhythm first, speed second. The keyboard isn't going anywhere. My fingers return home after every key. I let the text flow quietly through my hands, sentence by sentence. I don't chase the next word before I've finished the last. There is a kind of music in this steadiness. I listen for it and follow its lead.",
  3: "I love myself. I respect myself. I learn patiently and take another step forward each day. I just start with one calm sentence and return when I drift. I don't judge the drift — I simply notice and come back. This returning is its own kind of practice. It is enough to begin again, every time.",
  4: "I respect myself. My effort matters, even if I'm slower today than yesterday. I don't need to be perfect to make progress. I just return to practice and keep going. Slow days are still days of learning. I honor the work I show up to do. Every sentence typed is a small act of care for myself.",
  5: "You've got this. Even small progress is progress. Today you're doing something good for yourself and your rhythm. One calm round is better than zero perfect rounds. You don't need to feel ready to begin. The act of starting is already an achievement. Trust that today's effort is exactly what it needs to be right now.",
  6: "It has never been better than right now. I see progress I couldn't notice before. I learn calmly and that is truly enough. I return with a clear head and open hands. Each session adds something, even when it doesn't feel that way. I carry the practice forward without forcing it. The clarity comes in its own time.",
  7: "Fingers return to the home row. This is my point of calm. I start from here and return here after every mistake. The home row always waits for me. It holds no judgment — only presence. I press one key, then the next. The row beneath my fingers is a quiet and steady anchor I can always find.",
  8: "I breathe calmly. I type more slowly. When I slow down, I see more and make fewer mistakes. I focus only on the present character right in front of me. The next word can wait. I am only here, with this key, in this breath. Slowness is not weakness — it is attention given to what matters.",
  9: "Small steps build big change. One round today can be the start of a new habit. I don't need to type fast to type well. Rhythm builds slowly and steadily. Each session plants a seed I may not see sprout for weeks. I trust the quiet accumulation of practice. It is more than enough to simply show up.",
  10: "I don't correct. I carry on. A mistake is a trace of learning, not a verdict. Every sentence to the end, without backspace, without panic. I guide my hand through the text. Stopping would break the flow I am building. So I move through errors the way water moves through stone — patient, continuous, and unafraid.",
  11: "It's easy to add an apostrophe. I can't stop now. Don't worry — just keep going. I won't miss a single key. I've been here before and I know the rhythm. My hands remember what my mind sometimes forgets. The muscle memory is building quietly beneath each repetition. I trust what I have already practiced to carry me through.",
  12: "I'm learning the flow. That's what matters most. I don't need to rush — I've got time. It's not about speed, it's about control. I'll get there, one word at a time. Control comes from relaxing, not from gripping tighter. I let each word arrive on its own. The flow finds me when I stop chasing it.",
  13: "It is good that you are here. Your presence matters, even when nothing special happens. You don't need to do something great to be important. Those quiet moments last the longest. A gentle session leaves its mark just as surely as a hard one. You were here, and you tried. That is always enough to remember.",
  14: "You matter. Not because you do everything perfectly, but because you are yourself. Your rhythm, your pace, your mistakes — these all belong to you. You have the right to go your own way. No one else types quite the way you do, and that is not a flaw. Your particular way of learning is valid. Honor it without apology.",
  15: "You are not alone, even in moments that seem empty. In this silence there can be a peace deeper than words. You don't need everything figured out to feel that calm. The quiet room, the soft clicks, the steady breath — these are enough. You are held by the practice itself, whether you can feel it or not.",
  16: "I see myself calm, strong, and focused. I act as though it is already true — because that's what I'm building. My hands move with confidence. My mind is here, at this keyboard. I don't wait for confidence to arrive before I begin. I practice being it, and slowly it becomes real. This is exactly how it works.",
  17: "My goal is already ripening beneath the surface. Every action is a sign I'm getting closer. Seeds grow underground before the sprout appears. I work calmly and trust the process. I don't need to see the result to believe in the work. Patience is not passivity — it is faith in motion. I keep going without doubt.",
  18: "I don't need to control every single key. I learn to trust my hands and my rhythm. When I loosen my grip, the text flows more easily than when I tense up. Trust arrives through repetition, not through force. I practice letting go as much as I practice the keys. Both are essential parts of learning.",
  19: "The best moment to start doesn't always look grand. Sometimes it begins with one calm round without pressure. I sit down, type, and let it be what it is. This is that moment. There is no perfect setup, no ideal mood to wait for. I begin here, as I am, and that is the whole practice.",
  20: "When a mistake appears, I don't panic. I keep writing, sentence after sentence, to the very end. Calm is more important than a quick fix. I guide my hand through the text. Mistakes are part of the page, not damage to it. I write past them with what comes next. The text carries me forward, always forward.",

  // Chapter 2 — Flow, Self-trust
  21: "Progress doesn't need to announce itself. Sometimes it's quiet and precisely for that reason real. I prefer a steady rhythm that carries me further every day. Small results add up. I don't need to see the full picture at once. What matters is the next word, the next moment of care. Consistency does the work that effort alone cannot.",
  22: "I trust myself. My pace is enough. I don't need to prove my worth to anyone, because it doesn't depend on results or speed. Trusting myself is a quiet certainty that I'll manage. I don't need comparison to know where I stand. The ground beneath me is steady, and I built it slowly. That is something no result can take away.",
  23: "I choose calm. I choose patience toward myself and my own learning process. Not everything works the first time — and that is completely fine. Calm is a stance I choose regardless of result. Even when frustration rises, I notice it and let it pass. I return to patience the way I return to home row — reliably, without drama. It is always there waiting.",
  24: "My hands find rhythm when I stop getting in their way with impatience. When I return to basics, everything becomes simpler. Every finger knows where to go if I allow it. The body remembers what the mind forgets. I don't need to think through each movement — I need to trust what I've practiced. Presence is the only thing required.",
  25: "First I listen carefully. Then I write from memory, not from my eyes. I let the sentence return from where it paused. I trust what I remembered and guide my fingers forward. The words are already in me. I don't search for them — I allow them to rise. That space between reading and writing is where real learning lives.",
  26: "I keep getting better. The rhythm that once seemed unnatural now comes on its own. I don't force it — I allow it. That is the best kind of progress: the kind that simply arrives. I look back and see what used to be difficult. It isn't anymore. That quiet shift happened without fanfare, and it will keep happening.",
  27: "Don't let the apostrophe trip you. I've typed it hundreds of times and I won't stop now. It's just a key — no different from the rest. Step-by-step I move forward. The small things that once caught me are becoming familiar. Repetition turns hesitation into reflex. I meet each character with recognition now, not resistance.",
  28: "Well-trained hands know every corner of the keyboard. I've practiced this long enough. Don't hesitate — just reach and press. I find the key and I return home without breaking flow. My fingers know the distance. The path from home row to any key is a journey I've made a thousand times. I don't look. I trust and move.",
  29: "We grow together. When I help another person, something in me grows as well. A small gesture, an attentive word, a moment of real presence — that is enough. Connection starts small. It doesn't need to be grand to matter. I give what I have, and something returns that I didn't expect. That quiet exchange is what makes practice feel like more than practice.",
  30: "The sacred is not far away. It lives in small acts done with full attention. In these ordinary things there is something that holds us. A calm that doesn't need to be earned, only noticed. I don't have to look for it elsewhere. It's here in the rhythm of keys, in the pause between words. The ordinary moment, met with presence, is already sacred.",
  31: "I imagine my goal clearly. I see what I feel and what I'm doing when I arrive. That image draws me forward even when the road is long. I return to it and let it work quietly within me. The clearer the image, the more naturally my actions align with it. I don't force it — I invite it. The vision leads and I follow with patience.",
  32: "My future self is already practicing this. They sit at the same keyboard and type with greater ease. I am building toward that version of myself right now, with this sentence. Every word I type narrows the distance between who I am and who I am becoming. I trust the repetition. What I do today shapes the hands I'll have tomorrow.",
  33: "Once there was a student who typed very slowly. Every day she sat down and typed one sentence more than the day before. After a year, what she remembered was the patience she had learned. Not the speed — the patience. She had stopped measuring herself against others and only against yesterday. That shift was small and it changed everything.",
  34: "A river doesn't force its way. It finds the path of least resistance and keeps moving. When I type with that same spirit — no forcing, no panic — the words start to flow like water. I don't need to push. I only need to keep moving. Resistance eases when I stop fighting it. The current is already there. I trust it.",
  35: "No going back. I wrote it. It stays. The mistake is behind me now and I move forward. This is the practice of letting go: accepting what happened and continuing calmly. I don't carry the error into the next word. That moment is over. What remains is now — the next key, the next chance to be present.",
  36: "The sentence was there a moment ago. I held it in my mind and now I write from the inside out. I trust the trace the sentence left in me. My fingers know the way. I don't reach for the words — they come to meet me. The space between reading and writing is not a gap but a bridge. I cross it without rushing.",
  37: "Every session teaches me something. Sometimes a mistake. Sometimes a breakthrough. Either way I'm moving. I just show up, sit down, and type. The rest takes care of itself. I don't need perfection to make progress. Showing up consistently is its own skill, and I am building it. Whatever today brings, it counts.",
  38: "The keys are quiet under my fingers. The room is still. My breath goes in and out. In this moment I am exactly where I need to be: here, at this keyboard, in this calm. No hurry, no comparison. Just the quiet rhythm of thought becoming letter, letter becoming word. That is the whole of it, and it is enough.",
  39: "I am becoming the person I want to be. One session at a time, one sentence at a time, I move toward more skill. It takes time and that's fine. I trust the direction. I don't need to arrive quickly. Every day I sit down, I am a little more of who I am becoming. The movement is real even when I can't see it.",
  40: "Coming back is the practice. Not starting perfectly — returning. Every day I choose to sit down and try again. That is the whole secret: not talent, not speed, just the decision to return. I don't always feel ready. I return anyway. The keyboard is here and so am I. Each return is a small act of commitment, and they add up.",

  // Chapter 3 — EN Special Characters (apostrophes, hyphens, semicolons, colons)
  41: "It's easy once you've done it a hundred times. Don't worry — you won't miss it. I can't stop now; I won't stop now. That's how progress works: one keystroke at a time. What felt impossible becomes automatic. The fingers learn what the mind keeps repeating. I press on and the path gets clearer.",
  42: "I'm building well-worn habits day-by-day. Step-by-step, line-by-line, I find my rhythm. Long-form practice is just short-form practice repeated — it's that simple. Each session adds to the one before it. There's no shortcut; there's no trick. I show up, I type, and the habit grows stronger without me even noticing.",
  43: "Semi-colon usage; colon placement: these are the marks that give rhythm to writing. I type them calmly; I include every sign: comma, period, colon, dash, semi-colon. Each mark has a purpose; each pause has a meaning. I don't skip them — I lean into them. Punctuation is part of my fluency now: learned, practiced, owned.",
  44: "I've mastered the home row. Now I'm reaching further: up for numbers, sideways for punctuation. Reach, press, return — that's the whole idea. Simple as that. My fingers stretch without hesitation; they find the key and come back home. That return to center is the anchor. Every reach begins and ends with the home row.",
  45: "There's a reason I practice every day: progress. It's slow but it's real. Don't underestimate the small wins — they're the foundation. I've built something here and I won't stop. Each correct keystroke adds to what came before it. The foundation doesn't show, but it holds everything. I keep laying stones and the structure keeps rising.",
  46: "I'm not typing faster — I'm typing cleaner. One key at a time; no jumps, no panic; just steady rhythmic motion forward. It's working — I can feel it happening now. The noise in my fingers is quieting down. What used to feel frantic now feels measured. Clean is faster than fast — I believe that completely.",
  47: "I use colons to introduce: lists, examples, clarifications. I use semi-colons to connect: two thoughts; one sentence; one calm flow. My fingers know these keys now. I reach for them without looking; they're part of my vocabulary. Good punctuation isn't decoration — it's structure. I've made it mine: fluid, reliable, and always in the right place.",
  48: "Numbers appear inside sentences when I type amounts like 3 grams or 10 steps. The shift from letters to numbers and back is a rhythm I have trained. I maintain speed through it. Row 2 doesn't interrupt the flow anymore — it's part of it. 7 keys, 8 keys, back to letters: smooth and unbroken. Numbers are just another lane on the same road.",
  49: "I won't look at my hands. I type what I remember: each word, each comma, each apostrophe. I've practiced this enough. I trust my fingers and I let them lead me through. Looking down breaks the connection between eye and key. I keep my gaze ahead; I follow the text. My hands know where to go — they always have.",
  50: "One complete thought; then another. I write without stopping; without fixing; without judging. Just forward motion. That's what flow means: moving through text steadily and surely. I don't edit mid-sentence; I don't second-guess mid-word. The cursor moves forward and so do I. Flow isn't the absence of mistakes — it's the refusal to stop for them.",

  // Chapter 4 — New Rhythm, Expanded
  51: "A new chapter begins. I bring everything I learned and open to what comes next. The rhythm I built continues here, in new words, new sentences, new challenges. The foundation doesn't change — only the surface does. My hands are ready; my eyes are alert. What's new today will feel familiar by the end of this session.",
  52: "I write with more confidence now. My fingers remember the home row. My eyes move ahead in the text. My breath stays even. This is what consistency builds: not just speed, but ease. There's no struggle anymore — just motion. I read, I breathe, I type. The keyboard stopped being an obstacle; it became a tool I trust completely.",
  53: "Progress is quiet. It doesn't arrive with fanfare. One day you notice: this sentence is easier than it used to be. That's the whole reward — a small, private knowing that you improved. Nobody else sees it happen. There's no announcement; no certificate. Just you and the keyboard and the moment you realize you've grown. That's enough.",
  54: "I belong here. This keyboard is mine. This practice is mine. I don't need permission or perfect conditions. I sit down and I begin. The session starts the moment I decide to show up. I don't wait for motivation; motivation follows the action. I just start — and that first keystroke carries everything forward. Showing up is the whole practice.",
  55: "Every session is valid. Even the rough ones. Especially the rough ones. That's where I learn to stay steady when things don't go perfectly. Not perfection, but perseverance. A rough session that I finish is worth more than a perfect one I abandoned. I push through the friction; I meet the difficulty and stay. That's the practice within the practice.",
  56: "I set the pace. Not anyone else. Not the timer. I choose how fast I move, and I choose to move steadily. A pace I can sustain is worth more than a sprint I can't repeat. Sustainable speed compounds. What I can do today, I can do tomorrow — and a little more. I'm not racing; I'm building.",
  57: "My hands know this. My eyes read ahead. My breath connects both. When all three work together, the text flows through me like a conversation — natural, unforced, and clear. I don't chase that feeling; I invite it. Relax the shoulders; soften the grip; follow the line. When I stop trying so hard, the flow arrives on its own.",
  58: "I won't compare myself to yesterday if yesterday was hard. I show up today and give what today has. Some sessions are faster. Some are clearer. All of them count. Progress isn't linear — and I've stopped expecting it to be. Today is its own thing: its own starting point, its own effort. I type what I have, and that is enough.",
  59: "Back to basics when the basics feel hard. That is not regression — that is intelligence. I return to what works and rebuild from there. Simple, clear, slow. Then speed finds its way back. There's no shame in slowing down; there's wisdom in it. A reset isn't a step backward — it's a step onto solid ground. I rebuild and I come back stronger.",
  60: "The pause between keys is part of the rhythm too. I don't rush to fill every silence. I breathe and wait for the right moment. Timing is just as important as accuracy. A key pressed at the wrong speed is as disruptive as a key pressed wrong. I listen to the rhythm beneath the text. I type in time with it — and everything lands clean.",
  61: "I am capable of this. Not someday — now. With what I have, in the body I have, with the time I have. Right now I am capable of one more good sentence. That is enough. I don't need better conditions. I don't need more preparation. The moment is already here and I am already in it. That is all I need to begin.",
  62: "Mistakes are information. They tell me exactly where I need attention. I don't resent them — I read them. Then I correct my understanding and move on. The keyboard teaches me. Every error is a pointer showing me where the gap lives. I close that gap one keystroke at a time.",
  63: "I am patient with myself. Learning takes the time it takes. I cannot shortcut the muscle memory. I can only show up and do the work. I show up. I do the work. Patience is not passive. It is active trust — trust that the repetition is building something real inside me, even when I cannot yet see it.",
  64: "The end of this chapter is closer than the beginning. I have typed hundreds of sentences now. Each one has left a trace. I am not the same typist I was when I started. The distance I have traveled is real. I carry it in my fingers and in the way I hold my hands above the keys.",
  65: "I end each session with gratitude. For my hands. For the keyboard. For the time I gave myself. Even the short sessions matter. Even the imperfect ones. I practiced and that counts. Gratitude is not performance. It is the honest recognition that I chose this, showed up for it, and gave what I had.",

  // Chapter 5 — Deeper Rhythm, Full Attention
  66: "I carry the rhythm I built into every new text. It is mine now. Not a feature of the lesson, but something I hold in my hands. I bring it wherever I type. No one can take it from me. Each session deepens it. The rhythm is becoming a part of how I move through the world.",
  67: "I am the kind of person who finishes. Not the kind who gives up halfway. I finish the sentence. I finish the round. I finish the practice. That is who I am becoming. With every completed session, that identity grows stronger. I am not just hoping to be this person — I am proving it, right now.",
  68: "Full attention is a skill. Not everyone learns it. I am learning it right now, at this keyboard. Every time I bring my focus back from wandering, I am training my mind. The wander is not the failure. The return is the rep. Each return to the text makes me sharper and more present than before.",
  69: "A long text is just many short texts end to end. I don't type the whole thing — I type this sentence. Then the next. One at a time, I move through the longest piece without overwhelm. There is no mountain. There is only the next step. I take it. Then the one after. That is how long things get done.",
  70: "I bring calm to every character. Not just the easy ones — the tricky ones too. The shift keys. The punctuation. I slow down for them and get them right. That's how mastery is built. Speed will come later, carried on the back of accuracy. For now I choose precision and let it do its work.",
  71: "Each word is a small world. I pass through it key by key and then leave it behind. I don't linger. I don't revisit. I move forward through the text like a traveler through a landscape. The landscape changes with every line. Each word I type is a step taken, a place visited, a small thing completed.",
  72: "I have everything I need to do this. My hands are capable. My attention is here. The text is clear. There is nothing in my way. I simply type, and that is enough. I do not wait for better conditions. These conditions are the ones I have, and they are sufficient. I begin now.",
  73: "Forward only. I let the error stand and continue. The text will be imperfect but the session will be complete. A complete imperfect session teaches more than an abandoned perfect attempt. I am not chasing perfection. I am chasing completion. And completion, done with effort, is worth more than any flawless draft I never finished.",
  74: "Courage is quiet. It is choosing to try again after a failed round. It is sitting back down when part of me wants to walk away. I practice courage every time I open this training. It does not announce itself. It just shows up at the keyboard, fingers ready, and begins again without needing praise or permission.",
  75: "I see the finished line. I see myself completing this with clean hands and even breath. That image lives in my practice even when keystrokes feel difficult. I hold it steady. The image is not a fantasy. It is a destination I am already moving toward with every word I type.",
  76: "The screen and the keys are a system. My eyes read ahead and my fingers follow without lag. When the connection is smooth, I feel it: a current of flow that makes typing feel like play. I seek that current every session. I know it by how the effort disappears and only the movement remains.",
  77: "I am getting somewhere. Even when it doesn't feel like it. Every session I do something most people don't: I practice with intention. That distinction matters and it accumulates. The progress is real even when it is invisible. It is being stored in my hands and my habits, and it will show when it matters.",
  78: "Awareness without judgment. I notice the mistake and note it calmly. I do not catastrophize. I simply update my map and move forward. The path is still clear ahead of me. Clarity is not about having no errors. It is about not letting errors become fog. I see through them and keep moving.",
  79: "I reset when I need to. Not as defeat — as wisdom. I return to the home row, slow my breath, and begin again with fresh attention. Starting again is not failure. It is part of the process. Some of the best sessions begin with a reset. The pause is not wasted time — it is how I find my footing before I move.",
  80: "The rhythm of typing is its own form of meditation. Each keystroke is a breath. Each sentence is a cycle. When I surrender to the rhythm, the thinking stops and the doing takes over. I am not separate from the text. I am passing through it, breath by breath, until it is behind me and I am whole.",

  // Chapter 6 — Special Chars Deep Practice
  81: "I can place a colon exactly when I need it: right there, no hesitation. Word, space, colon — without slowing down. That's control. That's what practice looks like up close. The colon doesn't slow me. It arrives on time, fits into the flow, and the sentence continues without a gap.",
  82: "Does my finger know where the question mark is? Yes, it does. Does that mean I pause before I reach for it? No. My finger moves and finds the mark and returns. Smooth. The question mark lives above the slash. I know this. I don't look. I shift, I press, I release. The answer is always yes.",
  83: "Exclamation points mark the moments worth noting! I press them firmly, without drama! Then I return to baseline, because the next key is always the calm one that follows. Shift and 1 together — that's all it takes. I press, release, and move on. Emphasis doesn't cost me speed.",
  84: "Parentheses hold additional ideas (like this one) and I type them without pausing. I open, write the thought, then close — in one smooth sequence. I don't stop when symbols arrive. The open bracket is there. The close is right beside it. I reach, wrap the thought, and keep writing.",
  85: "I use quotation marks when I need to quote: \"Every key is a choice.\" I find the shift key and the quote key without looking down. That connection is built through repetition alone. I open, I write, I close. The marks frame the thought without slowing it. Repetition made this easy.",
  86: "The dash connects — quickly and smoothly — without breaking the flow. I type through it as if it were any other key. Reach, press, return. The em dash and hyphen are both mine now. One is longer, one is short, but both arrive the same way: without ceremony. I place them and continue. The sentence holds.",
  87: "Numbers appear inside sentences: 3 grams, 10 steps, 250 repetitions. The shift from letters to numbers and back is a rhythm I have trained. I maintain speed through the transition. My hand lifts, finds the digit, and returns. The sentence doesn't wait. I keep up with it.",
  88: "Brackets [like these] contain optional information. I find the bracket key just past the p and l. I press it without looking. I close it and continue. Nothing breaks my flow. The thought is wrapped and complete. My right hand handles these keys without instruction. They are mapped. I have been here before.",
  89: "A percent sign appears in data: 97% accuracy is a result worth noting. I reach for shift and 5 simultaneously. They arrive together. Then I release and return to the letters. The sign sits above the 5. I know this. The digit and its symbol come in one motion, then I'm back among the letters.",
  90: "I know every common symbol now. At sign, hash, ampersand, asterisk — I find them all. @ for email. # for tags. & to connect two thoughts. * to emphasize. I type them without pause. Each one lives above a number. Shift and the digit — done. They arrive on time. I don't stop for them.",

  // Chapter 7 — Blind Flow
  91: "I write from memory. My eyes don't wander to my hands or to the screen. I hold the image of the text in my mind and let my fingers trace what I remember. The image stays long enough. I follow it faithfully, word by word, until the last key lands and the thought is on the page.",
  92: "Fewer eyes, more feel. I listen to the rhythm of the keys and let that sound guide me. When I stop looking, I start knowing. The keyboard becomes an extension of thought. The clicks have a pattern. I hear the pace and match it. Fast where the words are easy. Steady everywhere else. Sound becomes a kind of sight.",
  93: "The internal keyboard is always with me. I close my eyes and see the layout. Each zone is familiar: left hand, right hand, top row, home row, bottom row. It's all mapped inside. I navigate without looking. The map is reliable. I trust it the same way I trust the alphabet — completely, without thinking.",
  94: "I can't see, but I go forward. The text I read a moment ago is still in me. I follow the trace it left. My fingers find the keys before my mind has finished telling them where to go. That is muscle memory at its fullest. Thought and motion overlap. By the time I know what I'm typing, it's already typed.",
  95: "Screen silence is a kind of freedom. Without the visual noise, I type from a quieter place. The text becomes internal. I am no longer reading — I am remembering. Then I write. No cursor blinking. No letters appearing. Just the feel of keys and the certainty that the words are going somewhere. I trust the silence.",
  96: "No peeking. I trust the layout I've practiced. I trust the muscle memory I've built. I reach for keys with confidence and find them where I know they will be. The hands never lie when the training is real. I've done this enough times. Confidence isn't a feeling anymore — it's a fact.",
  97: "I read the sentence. I let it settle. Then I close my eyes and write. Not perfectly — but completely. The words come back to me in pieces and I place them key by key. Some arrive early. Others come exactly when I need them. I follow the memory at its own pace.",
  98: "Darkness helps. Without distraction, the memory sharpens. The sentence I just read rises back to the surface when I call it. I follow it faithfully from first word to last. Nothing competes for my attention. The words are cleaner here. I recall them with less effort and place them with more.",
  99: "I keep going even when I'm not sure. The next word usually appears when I let myself reach for it instead of stopping to remember. Trust the reach. The key is there. Hesitation breaks the chain. Motion keeps it intact. I commit to the next word and it arrives. That is how trained memory works.",
  100: "I trust my hands. They have practiced enough. They know this layout. They know these words. I release them from my conscious control and watch them type what we both already know. It is a strange kind of partnership. I provide the intention. They provide the movement. The sentence appears without either of us working very hard.",

  // Chapter 8 — Visualization
  101: "I live as if my goal is already complete. I feel the ease and confidence of someone who has already arrived. This feeling is not a fantasy — it is a blueprint. I act from it. I speak from it. The future I am building is not something I wait for — it is something I already inhabit, one session at a time.",
  102: "I don't need a cape. I just need clarity. I see myself succeeding at this, clearly and specifically. That image does real work inside me even when I'm not looking at it. I return to it often — not as a wish but as a fact already in motion. The clearer I hold it, the more naturally I move toward it.",
  103: "The state of fulfillment is available right now. I don't wait for conditions to change. I choose the feeling first, and let it shape what I do. Feeling leads, action follows. When I practice from fullness rather than lack, everything shifts. I am not chasing something distant — I am expanding into something already here.",
  104: "I build the picture of my future in detail. I feel the floor under my feet, the keys under my fingers, the satisfaction in my chest. That detail makes the vision real. Real visions guide real behavior. I don't have to force my way there — I keep practicing from inside the picture until the picture becomes my life.",
  105: "I am already on my way. Not almost on my way — already. Each practice session confirms this. I am not waiting for the journey to begin. I am in it, moving, now. Every sentence typed is evidence. Every round completed is proof. I do not need to look ahead to know I am progressing. The movement itself is enough.",
  106: "I feel it now. The confidence, the ease, the calm mastery that I am building toward — I feel it in this moment, in this session, in this sentence. It is already in me. Not just as potential but as something alive and present. I am not rehearsing for a future version of myself. I am being that version, right here.",
  107: "A good life is built from good moments. I am in one right now. I am practicing, present, and intentional. That is not a small thing. That is exactly how good lives are made. Each session I show up for becomes part of the structure. I am not waiting for life to mean something. I am making it mean something, now.",
  108: "I take on a new identity: someone who types with calm and precision. That person sits here now. They breathe evenly. They type without panic. That is who I am choosing to be. Identity is not fixed — it is chosen and then practiced into existence. Every round I complete reinforces the choice. I am not pretending. I am becoming.",
  109: "It is already working. Beneath the surface, the practice is building something. The results may not be visible yet, but the foundation is being laid, one session at a time. I trust that process even when I cannot measure it. Growth that happens underground is still growth. The tree does not doubt its roots while they spread in the dark.",
  110: "My future self types with ease I have not yet reached. But they built that ease exactly the way I am building it right now: one round at a time, one choice at a time, here. There is no shortcut between us — only practice. And I am doing the practice. That alone makes me part of who they became.",

  // Chapter 9 — Spirituality
  111: "You are loved. Not because of what you have achieved, but because of who you are. That love doesn't depend on your results or your speed or your accuracy. It is simply there. It was there before this session and it will be there long after. You don't have to earn it or protect it. You only need to receive it.",
  112: "Peace is available in the quiet. Not earned by doing more, not unlocked by reaching a goal. It is here, in the space between keystrokes, in the moment before the next word arrives. I practice returning to it — not once, but again and again. The return itself becomes the practice. Stillness is not an absence. It is something I can choose.",
  113: "You are not alone. In the silence of a long practice session, there is a presence that accompanies you. Subtle, patient, unhurried. You don't need to explain yourself to it. It asks nothing except that you continue. And when you feel tired or doubtful, that presence doesn't leave. It simply waits, steady and close, until you find your way back.",
  114: "Grace doesn't announce itself. It arrives in small moments: the sentence that flows without effort, the round that somehow goes better than expected. I notice it and I'm grateful. I have learned to look for it in the ordinary — in a rhythm that holds, in a finger that finds the right key without searching. That, too, is grace.",
  115: "Prayer without words is still prayer. The act of sitting down and practicing with full attention is itself a kind of communion. I bring myself here. That is enough. I don't need the right posture or the right thoughts. I only need the willingness to show up. The practice receives that willingness and quietly turns it into something more.",
  116: "The divine doesn't keep a spreadsheet. It doesn't track your accuracy or count your backspaces. It sees the whole of you, not the score. That knowledge changes how I practice. I can let go of the need to perform and simply be present. What I bring to this session — my attention, my patience, my care — that is what matters.",
  117: "Light shows up in small movements. In the patience I choose when a mistake appears. In the breath I take before starting over. In the care I bring to each key. That is light. It doesn't require perfection. It only requires presence. And I can be present right now — in this word, in this key, in this quiet returning.",
  118: "I don't need to be ready. I just need to be willing. Readiness comes through practice, not before it. I show up imperfect and the practice meets me exactly where I am. That is the agreement: I come as I am, and I am met as I am. No prerequisites. No conditions. Just the willingness to begin, and the grace of being received.",
  119: "Gratitude is the simplest spiritual practice. I am grateful for this keyboard, this session, these hands, this moment. That gratitude transforms even a difficult round into something worthwhile. It shifts the frame from what is missing to what is present. And what is present right now is enough. I practice from here, I give thanks from here, and that changes everything.",
  120: "I am quietly led. Not driven, not pushed — led. By something in me that knows the way even when I don't. I follow that quiet guidance one sentence, one session, one day at a time. I don't need to understand it fully to trust it. I only need to keep showing up. And when I do, the path continues to reveal itself, one step ahead.",

  // Chapter 10 — Relationships
  121: "A father also comes back. After a hard day, he sits down at the table. He doesn't say much, but his presence is enough. Being there is its own language. We understand each other. The tiredness in his face tells a story we already know. We don't need it repeated. That is how families speak — quietly, and across years.",
  122: "Children watch everything. They learn how adults handle difficulty, frustration, patience, and return. I practice those things here so I can show them, not just tell them. They will carry what they see longer than what they hear. So I try to be worth watching. That is the deepest reason I keep coming back.",
  123: "I can't fix everything at once. I can only be present for this one conversation, this one moment, this one person in front of me. That is more than enough. That is everything. The urge to solve more, to reach further, to matter on a larger scale — I let it go. What is in front of me is already a whole world.",
  124: "It is good that you are here. Your presence fills something in the room that was empty before you arrived. You don't need to perform or achieve. Just being here is the gift. I mean that plainly, without flattery. Some people make a room feel fuller just by entering it. You are one of those people. The room knows it, even if you don't.",
  125: "Love in practice looks like showing up. It looks like doing the small things without making them into a production. It looks like staying when part of you wants to leave. It doesn't announce itself. It doesn't expect credit. It folds the clothes and wakes early and asks how the day was, and means it. That is the whole of it.",
  126: "I listen. Not to respond — to understand. I let the other person finish. I hold the silence that follows. In that silence is respect, and respect is the beginning of real connection. It takes practice. My first instinct is to fill the gap, to offer something, to be useful. But sometimes the most useful thing I can do is stay quiet and let what was said actually land.",
  127: "I don't need to be right. Being right is rarely what a conversation needs. What it needs is presence and willingness to hear something I didn't already know. That's harder and better. When I hold my opinion loosely, the other person relaxes too. The conversation goes somewhere neither of us planned. That is the best kind of conversation — the unscripted kind.",
  128: "Closeness is built in small moments, not grand gestures. A shared laugh. A cup of tea brought without being asked. A hand placed briefly on a shoulder. These are the bonds. They accumulate without anyone counting. Years later you can't point to the day it happened — closeness has no origin story. It just appears, quietly built from all those ordinary moments.",
  129: "Less defense. When I lower my walls even a little, something shifts. The conversation becomes a different kind of thing — not a negotiation, but a genuine meeting. That is worth the risk. The fear is that I will lose something by being open. But I have found the opposite. What opens in me seems to open something in the other person too. That is the gift of going first.",
  130: "A good word at the right moment changes something. I don't need many words. One honest, kind, well-placed word can reach somewhere that hours of talking cannot. I choose words with care. It takes patience — waiting for the right moment instead of filling every space. But when the moment comes and the word lands, you can see it in the other person's face. Something settles. Something opens.",

  // Chapter 11 — Stories
  131: "A note from a mother on the kitchen table, left before the house was quiet. Three lines. No signature. He read it standing up, still in his coat, and didn't move for a long moment. He read it again. Then he folded it along its original crease and put it in his shirt pocket, close to his chest, where it stayed for the rest of the day.",
  132: "The dog lay by the radiator every morning. He knew when his person was coming home — not by hearing or smell, but by something else, older than either. He was always right. At a certain hour he would rise and move to the door and wait. Not restlessly. Just with a quiet certainty that was almost like faith. The door always opened. He was never wrong.",
  133: "She ran after dark because the city belonged to her then. The streets were clear. The rhythm of her steps was the only clock. She wasn't running toward anything. Just running. The thinking stopped somewhere in the second mile. What replaced it was something cleaner — breath and motion and the soft percussion of feet. This was the only hour of the day that was entirely hers.",
  134: "The old keyboard had a worn space bar from years of use. He kept it on the desk after buying a new one. He never explained why. Some things don't need explaining. The new keyboard was quieter, more responsive. Better in every measurable way. But the old one held something the new one didn't — a record of all the years, pressed into the plastic without anyone meaning to leave it there.",
  135: "Rain on the window made the afternoon slow down. The coffee was still warm. There was nowhere to be. He typed because he wanted to, not because he had to. That was enough. The words came without pressure. Some were good. Some were not. He didn't stop to judge them. The afternoon was long and the rain kept falling and that was the whole of what he needed.",
  136: "She had been debugging the same function for three hours when she realized the error was in her assumptions, not in the code. That was the worst kind of bug to find — and the most instructive. The code had been right the whole time. She had not been. She made a note — not about the function, but about the kind of confidence that stops you from seeing clearly.",
  137: "A small room with one window. A desk that took up most of the floor. A chair that was slightly too tall. It was his best writing room. Space doesn't explain creativity. Something else does. He had tried nicer rooms — larger, quieter, better lit. Nothing came in those rooms. Here, with the ceiling low and the chair wrong and the light thin, something always came. He stopped trying to understand it.",
  138: "He came home and didn't say anything for twenty minutes. She knew not to ask. She made tea. He drank it. By the time the cup was empty, something had passed and he was himself again. This was how they had learned to handle things — not by talking them to pieces, but by letting time and warmth and quiet do the work that words couldn't. It always worked.",
  139: "She ran first, then typed. The run cleared something. The typing organized what was left. Together they made a whole evening of productive thinking — neither one would have worked alone. She had tried typing without running. She had tried running without typing. The order mattered. The sequence was the discovery. Some routines aren't arbitrary — they have a logic you learn by living them long enough.",
  140: "A regular evening. Dinner, a walk, a session at the keyboard. Nothing extraordinary. But later, when she thought about her good years, evenings like this one were what she remembered most. Not the trips, not the milestones. Just the ordinary texture of a life that felt like her own. The walk in the cooling air. The words that came easily. The sense that everything was, for now, exactly right.",

  // Chapter 12 — Mastery
  141: "The master doesn't shout. They don't hurry and they don't announce. They simply appear, do what is needed, and move on. Mastery is invisible precisely because it looks so effortless. You only notice its absence — when something is done badly, when the effort shows. The beginner announces every step. The expert has nothing to announce. The work itself is the only signal.",
  142: "Accuracy before speed. Always. A fast typist who makes frequent errors is slower than a careful typist who makes almost none. Clean first. Fast follows naturally from clean. Speed built on errors is borrowed time — you spend it correcting. Speed built on accuracy is real. It compounds. One clean keystroke at a time, the pace rises on its own.",
  143: "Stability is underrated. The ability to perform consistently, round after round, without peaks and crashes — that is a more valuable skill than occasional brilliance. Build the baseline. Peaks are exciting but they are not a foundation. A consistent 80 is worth more than an occasional 120. The athlete who is always ready beats the one who is sometimes extraordinary.",
  144: "I don't chase the score. The score is a summary of what already happened. I focus on what is happening now: this character, this word, this breath. The score takes care of itself. Chasing a number pulls me out of the moment that creates the number. The mind that is present produces the score. The mind that watches the score produces nothing.",
  145: "Less drama. When a difficult section arrives, I don't brace for it — I meet it. My hands know what to do. My job is to stay out of their way and let the practice speak. Tension is the enemy of speed. Anxiety about a hard passage adds friction before the first keystroke. I breathe, I soften, I trust what has been trained. Then I begin.",
  146: "Quiet power is the kind that doesn't need to prove itself. It shows up in the work, not in the announcement of the work. I build this kind of power session by session, without ceremony. No one needs to know how many hours I have put in. The hands remember. The results speak. Ceremony is for those still trying to convince themselves.",
  147: "Craft is attention given consistently over time. Not inspiration. Not talent. Just showing up with focus, doing the next thing well, and doing it again tomorrow. That is everything. Inspiration arrives occasionally and uninvited. Craft shows up every day because you made the choice. The gap between those who have skill and those who do not is mostly just that choice, repeated.",
  148: "Full presence is the highest technique. Not thinking about the previous key or the next word — only the current one. This moment only. That quality of attention is what mastery rests on. Attention can be trained like a muscle. Each time the mind wanders and returns, it grows stronger. The session is not just typing practice — it is attention practice.",
  149: "I don't run from the difficult lessons. I sit with them longer. I type the hard sentence a second time, a third time. Not as punishment — as study. The difficulty is the teacher. Frustration is just resistance to the lesson. When I feel it rising, I slow down rather than push through. Slowness dissolves what force cannot. The hard becomes known.",
  150: "777 words per minute is a number. What's behind that number is ten thousand hours of someone choosing to return, choosing to focus, choosing to do the work again. I am building that. Every session adds one layer. No single session is the one that matters — all of them do. The number is just the visible surface. Beneath it is ten thousand mornings of showing up.",
};

// Appending chapters 13-25
Object.assign(lessonTextsEN, {
  // Chapter 13 — Jade Path I (short, difficulty 2)
  151: "The blade doesn't need to shine to be sharp. A person doesn't need to shout to have power. Silence first, then movement. The one who speaks least in the room often carries the most. Their words, when they come, land cleanly. Their actions need no announcement. Polish is for show. The edge is for work.",
  152: "Bamboo bends in the storm and stands again after. Bamboo does not resist — it absorbs. That is why it cannot be broken. I practice the way of bamboo. When a session goes wrong, I bend with it. When my fingers stumble, I don't stiffen — I yield, reset, continue. The storm passes. The practice stands. That is bamboo.",
  153: "The master breathed before he moved. Not to delay — to begin from stillness. The breath was not preparation. The breath was the first technique. I do the same before each session. The hands settle. The shoulders drop. The eyes soften. What begins in the body begins in the right place. The keys wait.",
  154: "Rain fell in the courtyard all morning. No one moved. The master sat with his tea and watched. When the rain stopped, the lesson began. Waiting had been the lesson. The students who grew restless had missed it. Patience is not the pause before mastery — it is mastery. The one who can wait without resistance has already learned something most never will.",
  155: "The first bow is not a gesture of weakness. It is the student's declaration: I am here to learn. Everything that follows is made possible by the sincerity of that first bow. Pride blocks the door. Humility opens it. The greatest learners are those who can bow regardless of what they already know. They bow before each lesson, each session, each attempt.",
  156: "A leaf on the water doesn't fight the current. It moves with it, around every stone, through every bend. I practice moving with what comes, not against it. When speed drops, I don't force it back. When a word trips me, I don't carry it into the next. The leaf doesn't mourn the stone. It is already gone, still moving.",

  // Chapter 14 — Jade Path II (difficulty 3, longer)
  157: "Each ring was a lesson. One taught patience, another courage, a third silence. The last reminded us that the greatest power needs no noise. It simply acts. We spent a year studying the rings before we were given anything to practice. That was the practice. Understanding what each lesson asked of us before we were trusted to carry it.",
  158: "The house of flying thoughts is everywhere. Thoughts land and take off without permission. The practice is not to stop them — it is to let them pass without following. The beginner chases each thought out of the house. The practitioner leaves the door open. What passes through does not disturb what is happening at the keys. The work continues, uninterrupted.",
  159: "A hero without an audience is the truest kind. No applause, no record, no witness. Just the work done because it is right. That kind of heroism lasts longer than any monument. Monuments erode. Witnessed acts grow complicated over time — what they meant and who was watching. But the act done alone, in private, for no gain, is clean. It belongs entirely to the one who did it.",
  160: "The school of shadow teaches what sunlight cannot. Difficulty reveals what ease conceals. The master sends students into shadow not to break them, but to show them what they carry. Most come back changed not by what was hard, but by what they discovered in themselves while it was. The shadow is a mirror. Few students understand this until they have stood in it.",
  161: "She didn't speak for three days. Not from sadness, not from anger — from choice. When she finally spoke again, every word had more weight. Silence had charged the language. People leaned in. They heard her differently. She understood then that silence is not the absence of speech — it is the ground in which speech takes root and grows heavy with meaning.",
  162: "Stillness is the preparation for movement. Movement is the expression of stillness. They do not oppose each other. They teach each other. I hold both at once. When I am still, I am already moving inside. When I move, the stillness travels with me. There is no pure stillness, no pure motion — each contains the other, the way a held breath contains the next exhale.",
  163: "The water drip cut through stone not by force but by return. It went away and came back. Again and again, in the same place, without fail. That is the whole secret. Not power — fidelity. Not effort — return. The stone did not surrender its hardness. The water did not abandon its softness. And still, in time, the water won.",
  164: "The student asked: how long until I understand? The teacher said: understanding arrives the moment you stop looking for it. The student sat with that answer for a long time. Then one afternoon, not thinking about it at all, something opened. No fanfare. No announcement. It was simply there, the way sunlight arrives when the clouds part — not new, just no longer hidden.",
  165: "The mountain does not go anywhere. It simply stands. When the storm arrives, it does not brace or flee. It is already everything the storm can do anything to. I practice standing. Not with rigidity — with depth. The tree that bends survives because its roots hold. I am learning where my roots are. I am learning to be moved without being swept away.",
  166: "Speed without intention is just noise. I move deliberately — not slowly, not cautiously, but with a clarity of purpose that makes each action complete in itself. The arrow does not hurry to its mark. It arrives because it was fully released. I practice that release — the kind of speed that comes not from rushing but from removing everything in the way.",
  167: "Every loss carries a teaching. The student who won every match learned the least. It was the one who lost, then returned, then lost again, and still returned, who became the master. Winning teaches you what works. Losing teaches you what you are. And what you are — beneath the strategy, beneath the technique — is the only thing that holds when the real pressure arrives.",
  168: "The night before the tournament, the student did not practice. She slept. The master approved. Rest is part of the preparation. The body knows how to get ready if you let it. All the training was still there, settled into her muscles, her timing, her nerves. Sleep did not erase it. Sleep pressed it deeper. She woke more ready than she had been the night before.",
  169: "A warrior who has made peace with failure is the most dangerous kind. She no longer fears the fall. She has learned to use the ground as a teacher and rise from it with new understanding. Fear of falling is what keeps most people small — they hold back, they hedge. She does not. She enters fully, knowing that if she falls, she has been there before. The floor does not frighten her.",
  170: "The jade path is not a destination. It is a way of walking. You don't arrive at the jade path — you realize, one day, that you've been on it all along without knowing. That realization changes nothing and everything. Your steps do not change. Only the quality of your attention shifts. You are no longer searching for the path. You are simply walking, and that turns out to be the path.",

  // Chapter 15 — Jade Path III (difficulty 4, longer still)
  171: "The bridge over the mist looked like it led nowhere. But every step revealed the next part of the path. That is how practice works: you can only see as far as you're willing to walk. The fog does not lift all at once. It thins slowly, with each deliberate step forward. There is no shortcut to the other side. There is only the next plank beneath your feet, and the willingness to trust it.",
  172: "Stillness before movement is the secret that cannot be spoken, only understood through practice. The body that is still before it moves is capable of something the tensed body never is. This is not a trick of technique but a truth of nature. Grip tightens what it seeks to hold. Release opens what grip closes.",
  173: "She had practiced the same form ten thousand times. Tonight it was different — not because she did anything differently, but because she finally stopped trying to do it right. Her hands moved without instruction. Her breath arrived without being called. The form had always known the way.",
  174: "The old temple had no roof on the east wing. The master insisted it stay that way. Rain came in. Students complained. He said: learn to practice in weather that is not your preference. One student left. The rest stayed. Their fingers grew cold. Their strokes did not waver. Discomfort, the master said, is just another teacher.",
  175: "A sword held too tightly cannot be quick. A mind held too tightly cannot be clear. The grip that seems like control is actually restriction. Release a little, and everything opens. The archer who strains draws crooked. What we clutch, we crush. Ease is not the absence of effort. It is effort finding its natural shape.",
  176: "Two students climbed the same mountain. One counted the steps. One watched the sky. At the top, both had arrived. Only one knew where they had been. They descended together. One remembered numbers. One remembered light. The mountain was the same for both. The experience was not.",
  177: "The lesson that never lands in one session arrives one day without warning, fully formed, as if it had been growing underground. I plant the seed each time I return to practice. The fingers remember what the mind could not hold. Repetition is not failure repeating itself — it is water finding its level, slow and certain. What felt impossible last week feels obvious today, and I cannot point to the moment it changed. That invisibility is the nature of deep learning. I trust the process most when I understand it least.",
  178: "He had been teaching for forty years. Students came from everywhere to learn from him. When asked what he had mastered, he said: patience with my own ignorance. That is still the practice. He never claimed to have arrived. Each morning he sat down and began again. His students learned more from his questions than his answers.",
  179: "To practice under pressure is to discover your actual level — not the level you perform at when conditions are perfect. Pressure is the truest teacher. I welcome it. When the stakes are real, excuses fall away. My fingers must move with purpose, not comfort. Difficulty is not an obstacle — it is the path.",
  180: "The form is a map, not the territory. The territory is what happens when you've done the form so many times you've forgotten you're doing a form. That is when it becomes real. The fingers stop searching. The mind stops managing. You are no longer following the path — you have become it.",
  181: "She entered the room quietly and stood at the back. No one noticed her arrive. She watched for an hour without moving, without speaking, without being seen. The room filled and emptied around her like a tide. When she left, she carried more than anyone who had spoken. Presence, it turned out, required no words. Only attention, and the patience to hold it.",
  182: "The longest journeys begin with a stillness so complete that the first step feels like an event. I find that stillness. I let it be complete. I do not hurry it or fill it with preparation. The stillness is the preparation. When it is ready, I am ready. Then I begin, and the beginning means something.",
  183: "Rain, cold, discomfort, noise — these are not obstacles. They are conditions. The practice that works only in ideal conditions is no practice at all. I train in every condition. I train when I am tired. I train when I am distracted. I train when the environment refuses to cooperate. The practice does not require comfort. It requires only that I show up.",
  184: "At the deepest level, technique dissolves. What is left is not skill — it is character. The way a person moves when they have forgotten to move correctly is who they actually are. This is why the long work matters. You are not building a performance. You are building a person. The technique is the scaffold. What stands when the scaffold comes down is you.",
  185: "Five years of practice, and he finally understood the first lesson. Not because he hadn't heard it — he had heard it hundreds of times. He had nodded at it, repeated it back, even taught it to others. But understanding from the outside is not understanding at all. He finally understood it from the inside. He understood it in his hands, in his breath, in the way he no longer needed to think.",
  186: "The master's only instruction was: return. Return to the form. Return to the practice. Return to the beginning. Students waited for more. There was no more. They looked for hidden meaning. The meaning was not hidden — it was plain. That word — return — contained everything else. The wandering attention, the skipped session, the lost confidence: all of it answered by the same instruction. Return.",
  187: "The student wanted to learn the advanced techniques. The master made her practice the basic ones for two more years. The student was frustrated. She practiced anyway. The frustration became boredom. The boredom became ease. The ease became something she had no word for. By then, she had stopped wanting the advanced ones. She understood now why the master had refused. She had something better. She had arrived somewhere the advanced techniques could not take her.",
  188: "Endurance is not the same as stubbornness. Endurance knows why it continues. Stubbornness has forgotten. The stubborn person pushes harder when the way is wrong. The enduring person pauses, recalibrates, and continues. I practice endurance: I know why I sit down each time. When the session is hard, I return to that reason. I don't grip. I don't force. That knowing sustains me through the parts that don't.",
  189: "Before mastery, a technique is a collection of instructions. After mastery, it is a single movement with no instructions needed. The instructions have not disappeared — they have been absorbed. Every step that once required thought now happens without it. Between those two states is the whole of training: the long, unglamorous work of making conscious things unconscious. I am somewhere in that between. I keep moving.",
  190: "She bowed before leaving the mat. Not as ceremony — as acknowledgment. Something had happened here that deserved recognition. She had entered uncertain and left steady. Not confident — steady. There is a difference. Confidence believes it cannot fail. Steadiness has already failed, many times, and knows it will survive. She was not exactly who she had been when she arrived. The bow marked that change, quietly, without fanfare. That was enough.",

  // Chapter 16 — Gaming (difficulty 1-4)
  191: "I build my base calmly. First the foundation, then the walls. Rushing the build is how the structure fails. I place each piece with intention and check what I've built before I add more. I don't need everything at once. One structure at a time, the base becomes something real. What took longer to build takes longer to fall. That's worth knowing.",
  192: "Every mistake is a respawn, not a game over. I don't lose time to regret — regret is just delay in another form. I return to the round, assess what went wrong, correct my rhythm, and keep playing. The session ends when I decide it ends. The game is still going and so am I. Mistakes are just the cost of playing.",
  193: "The loot of patience drops rarely but its value is legendary. Some players never see it — they quit the grind before the drop rate favors them. I farm it every session. No rush, no skip, no shortcut around the parts that feel slow. The slow parts are the farming. I wait for it and when it comes, I recognize it immediately. I know what it's worth because I know what it cost.",
  194: "I read the map before I move. Unplanned movement is wasted movement. I study the layout, identify the choke points, mark what I know and what I don't. I know where the threats are. I know where the exits are. I know which paths look fast but aren't. I choose my route calmly and I move through it without hesitation. Preparation is half the execution.",
  195: "Respawn cooldown is the pause between attempts. Most players waste it. They tilt, they rage, they re-enter the match carrying the last mistake like extra weight. I use it well. I don't carry what I can't use. I breathe, I think about what happened without attaching emotion to it, and I re-enter the match with a better read. The cooldown is not dead time. It is prep time.",
  196: "I grind the skills that matter. Not the flashy ones — the consistent ones. Flash is visible. Consistency wins. Accuracy. Positioning. Recovery. These are not the skills that get clipped, that get replayed, that get praised in the lobby. These are the unglamorous skills that separate good players from great ones. I am not building a highlight reel. I am building a foundation.",
  197: "Health is the resource that matters most. I protect it before I protect anything else. I don't trade it for short-term gains or aggressive plays that look good but don't pay off. Positioning is how I keep it. Patience is how I protect it. A player at full health who moves slowly is worth more than one who sprints into damage. Survive first. Everything else follows.",
  198: "The meta changes. My fundamentals don't. What works this season may be nerfed next season. The environment shifts, the targets move. I don't chase the shifting target. Build speed, accuracy, and calm — those transfer to every patch, every update, every new challenge that appears. Skills built on trends expire. Skills built on fundamentals compound. I invest in the skills that last.",
  199: "PvP teaches you what PvE cannot: how to adapt in real time, under pressure, against an unpredictable opponent. PvE gives you patterns you can memorize. PvP gives you chaos you must read. Every challenging session is a PvP match. The opponent is not always another player — sometimes it is the pace, the difficulty, the moment when familiar things stop feeling familiar. I treat it that way.",
  200: "I build higher, but I don't forget the foundation. Reaching further out means knowing exactly where to return. The home row is my base. Every extension away from it is measured against it. That's where my fingers return — without looking, without thinking, without error. The higher I build, the more I value what's underneath. A tall structure stands only as well as its base.",
  201: "I don't need to see the whole map. I need the nearest point, one good move, and a little courage. That's enough to advance. The rest reveals itself when I'm already moving. Clarity doesn't come from standing still. It comes from committing to the next step and trusting what follows. Motion is its own kind of knowledge.",
  202: "Focus mode: on. Notifications off. Ambient sound on. I enter the session as if entering a match that matters. Because it does. Every session counts on the leaderboard of my progress. I don't show up halfway. I bring everything I have to this window of time. The ritual prepares the mind. The session is where it proves itself.",
  203: "The best speedrun strategy is the one that doesn't break. I don't go for the fastest possible route — I go for the most reliable one. Consistency beats brilliance in the long run. A shortcut that fails twice costs more than the steady path taken once. I build on habits that hold, not on tricks that only work when everything goes right.",
  204: "I min-max the right things. Not damage output — practice quality. Not gear score — accuracy rate. I optimize for what actually improves me, not for what looks impressive. Vanity stats are noise. Real progress lives in the metrics no one posts about. I track what changes my performance, not what fills my showcase.",
  205: "A well-timed dodge is better than maximum armor. In typing as in games, agility matters. I don't tank through mistakes — I step around them with precision and awareness. Brute force has its limits. I read the pattern, anticipate, and move before the hit lands. That's not luck. That's practice.",
  206: "The tutorial was longer than I expected. But I did it completely. I didn't skip it. The details it taught me show up now in every session in ways I couldn't have predicted. Impatience tells you to rush past the fundamentals. Experience shows you why they mattered. The time I spent at the beginning shortened every step that came after.",
  207: "Every game has a learning curve. The fastest way through it is to accept that you're on it. Stop resisting the curve. Embrace the arc. You'll get to the top of it sooner if you don't fight it. Frustration is just the curve steepening for a moment. It doesn't mean you're failing. It means you're climbing. Keep moving. The plateau comes, and when it does, you'll have earned it.",
  208: "The server remembers my score but not my effort. I remember my effort. I know what each session cost and what it built. That record matters more than any public leaderboard. Numbers compress everything into a single line. The real story is the hour I stayed when I wanted to quit, and the run I repeated until it clicked.",
  209: "The final boss requires everything you've learned. The patterns come faster, the margins get smaller. But by the time you face it, you have exactly what you need. You built it for this. Every hard session was a piece of the answer. Every time you pushed through the resistance was a rep toward this moment. Nothing was wasted. It was all preparation.",
  210: "The server legend doesn't win because they never lose. They win because after every loss they come back with better understanding. Losing and returning — that is the whole game. The loss itself teaches what the win can't. You see your gaps only when they get exposed. So you study the defeat, adjust, and come back different.",

  // Chapter 23 — Emerald Tablets
  273: "I, Thoth the Atlantean, master of mysteries, keeper of records, mighty in wisdom, write these words for those who seek the Light in the darkness of ages. Let all who read herein take heed, for these words are drawn from the deep wells of eternal knowing, given freely to those whose hearts are open and whose will is steadfast and true.",
  274: "Hear ye, O man, and list to my voice. List to the wisdom I give unto thee. Seek ye in the pathway that leads to the Light. Open your heart to the knowledge hidden in darkness. Cast away the veil of illusion that blinds thine eyes and know that the Light dwelleth within thee even now, waiting to blaze forth as a great fire in the night of ages.",
  275: "Know ye that all of the future is clear to the Master who reads the book of the past. Seek ye to read the patterns of the present and you shall know the future. The great wheel of ages turns and turns again, and what was shall be once more. He who knows the cycle of things holds the key to all doors, and no truth shall be hidden from him throughout all the ages.",
  276: "In the beginning, thou hast nothing. In the end, thou shalt have all. The key lies in the space between nothing and all things. Seek thou the middle way, for it is there that true wisdom abides. Neither cling to what passes nor flee from what comes, but stand steadfast in the Light and all knowledge shall be given unto thee in its proper hour.",
  277: "Light is life and life is Light. Gather the Light in the darkness of night and thou shalt find the way to eternal Light. Walk ye in this Light and let it guide thee. As the dawn drives back the long shadows of night, so shall the Light within thee drive back all that is dark and lost. Fear not the darkness, O man, for where Light truly dwelleth, darkness cannot long remain.",
  278: "Man is a star bound to a body until in the end he is freed through his strife. Only by struggle and toiling thy utmost shall the star within thee bloom out in new life. Know that every trial placed before thee is a gift of wisdom, and every hardship a step upon the upward path. As metal is made bright and strong in the forge of fire, so too is the soul made radiant through the trials of ages.",
  279: "Know that the future is never fixed. All paths are open to those who seek in purity of heart. The door stands before thee, the key is within thee, the path is thine to choose. Let not the shadow of fear hold thee at the threshold of the great unknown. Step forward in confidence and the way shall open before thee, for the Light guideth all who walk in sincerity and seek with an earnest heart.",
  280: "Seek thou the way to the eternal. Seek thou the Light on thy way. Speak thou in words without voice to those who dwell in the darkness, that they too may find the path. For among all gifts, the greatest is the sharing of the Light that has been found. In giving thou dost receive, and in lighting the way for another soul, thine own path shall grow ever brighter and more clear.",
  281: "He who knows the beginning of all things holds the key. He who holds the key finds all doors open and walks through the worlds in the Light that never goes out. Seek thou the beginning not in the world without, but in the deep silence that dwells within thee. There shalt thou find the source of all Light, and knowing it, thou shalt walk free through all the ages of creation.",
  282: "Look into thy heart and find there the wisdom that sleeps and waits. Call it forth and it shall answer. The truth was in thee all along, waiting to be known. Be still and let the voice of the deep speak within thee. In the silence between thy thoughts abides all knowledge and all Light. Turn not away from what thou findest there, but embrace it and let it be thy guide forevermore.",
  283: "As above, so below. As within, so without. The Law that governs all things moves through all planes, all times, all forms, and speaks in the voice of silence. What is mirrored in the heavens is lived out in the earth, and what moves in the vast is also moving in the small. One Law. One pattern. One truth beneath all veils.",
  284: "Time is a river that flows without end. Dive into its depths and you shall find there the beginning and the end as one, joined in the circle of all that is and ever shall be. The swimmer who fears the current shall drown. The one who yields to it is carried to the shore of knowing. There is no past that is truly gone and no future that is truly distant.",
  285: "The darkness is not the absence of Light. It is Light not yet unfolded. All things move toward the Light, even the stones, even the stars, even the sleeping heart of man. As the seed stirs in the cold earth long before the bloom, so the spirit turns toward its source before it wakes to knowing. Do not curse the darkness. It is only waiting to become.",
  286: "I passed through the barriers of shadow and stood in the halls of Amenti. There I learned: the soul that knows itself knows all things. Self-knowledge is the master key. For the cosmos is not out there, locked in distant spheres. It is here, folded within the one who seeks. The seeker who turns inward without flinching shall find that what was hidden was never hidden at all.",
  287: "Speak the word and the Light shall respond. Think the thought and the thought shall create. Know the truth and the truth shall set free the soul that has waited in darkness. For all things begin in the unseen and move toward form. The universe bends toward intention when intention is pure. Let the word be true, let the thought be clear, and what is asked of the silence shall be answered.",

  // Chapter 24 — Bhagavad Gita
  288: "The soul is never born nor dies at any time. It has not come into being and will not cease to be. It is unborn, eternal, ever-existing. When the body is slain, the soul is not slain. It was present before the first breath drew in and shall endure beyond the last light of the eyes. As fire passed from torch to torch is not thereby diminished, so the soul passes through its forms unchanged in nature and eternal in being.",
  289: "Just as a person puts on new garments, giving up old ones, the soul accepts new material bodies, giving up the old and useless ones. Change of form is not death of essence. The river is not lost when it leaves the mountain. The flame is not ended when it passes from one wick to another. What appears as ending is only transformation, and the one who knows this does not grieve.",
  290: "The soul can never be cut to pieces by any weapon, nor burned by fire, nor moistened by water, nor withered by the wind. It is beyond all such things. No force that arises in the world of matter holds any claim upon it. The sword reaches only what the soul has borrowed. What weeps at loss and trembles at threat has not yet found the ground that cannot be touched.",
  291: "One who has taken birth is sure to die, and after death one is sure to be born again. Therefore, in the unavoidable discharge of duty, thou shouldst not lament. Grief belongs to those who mistake the form for the truth. The wise see only the turning of the great wheel, and they stand at the center unmoved, fulfilling what was given to them without complaint and without fear.",
  292: "Let right deeds be thy motive, not the fruit which comes from them. Let the motive for action be in the action itself, not in the event. Act rightly and release the result. For the archer who fixes the eye upon the prize and not the mark shoots wildly. But the one who has learned to be still in the moment of release finds the arrow has already found its home.",
  293: "He who performs his duty without attachment, surrendering the results, is unaffected by sinful action, as the lotus leaf is untouched by water. Detachment is freedom. The world may pour its floods upon the lotus and leave it shining, turned always toward the light. So too the one who has learned the art of release moves through all weathers of joy and sorrow remaining ever whole, ever clear, ever free.",
  294: "Even if you are considered the most sinful of all sinners, you shall cross all the ocean of misdeeds with the boat of knowledge alone. Knowledge is the greatest raft. As fire does not refuse to purify the dross-laden ore, so the fire of wisdom withholds itself from no soul that reaches for it. No darkness is too deep, no burden too heavy, for the one who has truly come to know.",
  295: "As all rivers flow into the sea yet the sea is never filled, all desires merge into the person at peace. Such a one gains the highest peace — not those who crave objects. The sea does not run to meet the rivers, yet they come. The sky does not reach for the clouds, yet it holds them. So the one who has learned stillness finds all things drawn toward them, and the one who has ceased to grasp finds the hands are full.",
  296: "He who is not disturbed in mind even amidst miseries, who is not elated by happiness, and who is free from attachment, fear, and anger — he is called a sage of steady mind. The world moves in its ceaseless cycles of heat and cold, of rise and ruin, of praise and blame. The sage sits at the still center and watches without being moved, knowing that the storm passes and the ground beneath it does not change.",
  297: "Guard your thoughts, for they become words. Guard your words, for they become actions. Guard your actions, for they become habit. Guard your habits, for they shape your destiny. What a man tends in the secret garden of his mind grows in time to fill his days and form his face. The seed of a thought becomes the fruit of a life. Take care, therefore, what you plant and what you water.",
  298: "Surrender all your works to Me. Free yourself from longing and the sense of mine. Fight on — freed from burning fever of the soul. Do your duty and be at peace. For the hand that clings too tightly loses what it holds, and the heart that hungers for the outcome is never fed. What you release is not gone but transformed, returned to you purified beyond what you could have made of it yourself.",
  299: "The inner war is the hardest. To conquer the self is greater than to conquer armies. The warrior who masters the mind has won the only battle that truly matters. Kingdoms rise and crumble, and the names of great conquerors are lost to dust. But the one who stands victorious over his own restless nature has won a dominion that no force, no time, no turning of fortune shall ever overthrow.",
  300: "Fix your mind on Me, be devoted to Me, worship Me, bow down to Me. So shall you come to Me. I promise you truly, for you are dear to Me. Come as you are. Bring the weariness of long roads and the wounds of old wandering. Bring the questions that found no answer and the nights that found no end. For I have waited, and what turns toward the light is already on the path home.",
  301: "The mind is the friend of the conditioned soul, and his enemy as well. For him who has conquered the mind, the mind is the best of friends. For him who has failed, it is the greatest enemy. A tamed mind is a steady lamp in the long passage. An untamed mind is a fire that burns the shelter one seeks to build. The wise do not flee from the mind, nor do they surrender to it. They study its nature and learn to use it well.",
  302: "Let a man lift himself by his own self; let him not degrade himself. The self alone is the friend of the self, and the self alone is the enemy of the self. No other hand can do the work that was given to yours. No outside force can raise what only the soul can raise. Yet this is not burden but gift, for it means that what rises in you cannot be stopped by anything that stands outside of you.",

  // Chapter 25 — Tao Te Ching
  303: "The Tao that can be named is not the eternal Tao. The name that can be spoken is not the eternal name. Nameless: the beginning of heaven and earth. Named: the mother of ten thousand things. Ever desireless, you see the mystery. Ever desiring, you see only its surface.",
  304: "When beauty is recognized, ugliness has been learned. When good is recognized, evil has been learned. So being and not-being produce each other. Opposites arise together. Difficult and easy define one another. High and low lean upon each other. The sage works without preference and teaches without speaking.",
  305: "Water is fluid, soft, and yielding. But water will wear away rock. Whatever is rigid and blocked will be overcome. Whatever is soft and yielding will outlast the hard and strong. The tree that bends survives the storm. The branch that breaks was too proud to bow. True strength hides in softness.",
  306: "Simplicity, patience, compassion — these three are your greatest treasures. Simple in actions and thoughts, you return to the source. Patient with friends and enemies, you accord with the way things are. Compassionate toward yourself, you are reconciled with all beings. Hold these three things close. They are ancient, sufficient, and true.",
  307: "Knowing others is wisdom. Knowing yourself is enlightenment. Overcoming others takes force. Overcoming yourself takes true strength. Mastering others is power. Mastering yourself is freedom. Knowing enough is wealth. Following the Tao even in death is to live forever.",
  308: "Act without acting. Do without doing. Taste without tasting. The sage accomplishes without accumulating, acts without attachment, succeeds without dwelling on success. Give without expecting. Speak without grasping. Move without forcing. This is how the sage flows through the world.",
  309: "The great Tao flows everywhere. Ten thousand beings depend on it. It doesn't seek fame or credit. It can be called small. Yet ten thousand beings turn to it — it can also be called great. Because it never strives to be great, it achieves greatness. The sage, too, never reaches for glory — and so it comes.",
  310: "The highest good is like water. Water gives life to ten thousand things and does not compete. It goes to the lowly places that people disdain. That is why it is so close to the Tao. In dwelling, be close to the earth. In thinking, keep it simple. In conflict, be fair. Do not contend — and no one will contend with you.",
  311: "Who stands on tiptoe does not stand firm. Who rushes ahead does not go far. Who tries to shine dims his own light. Who defines himself cannot know who he really is. Who clings to his work will leave no legacy. Who forces his will loses his way. The sage lets go and endures.",
  312: "True words are not beautiful. Beautiful words are not true. The good are not argumentative. The argumentative are not good. Those who know are not full of theory. The sage does not compete — and so no one can rival him. He gives freely, and yet he has more.",
  313: "Thirty spokes share the wheel's hub. It is the center hole that makes it useful. Shape clay into a vessel — it is the space within that makes it useful. What is not there works. Cut doors and windows for a room — the emptiness within is what you enter. Being gives form. Non-being gives use.",
  314: "The great Tao is a vast river. It flows everywhere. Ten thousand things depend on it. It does not call them home, but all things return. The way does not force — it allows. It nourishes without possessing. It guides without commanding. It claims no dominion over any creature. It asks for nothing — and so it lacks nothing.",
  315: "The way of heaven is like a bow. What is high is pressed down; what is low is lifted up. What is too full is diminished; what is not enough is increased. The way restores balance. The way of people is otherwise — they strip the poor to enrich the wealthy. Only the sage gives freely and keeps no reward.",
  316: "The more you know, the less you understand. The more you accumulate, the less you have. The more you force, the less you achieve. Return to the root, and everything opens. Stop seeking, and you will find. Stop grasping, and it will come to you. The empty hand receives. The quiet mind sees.",
  317: "Be quiet. Listen. The truth is not loud. It comes in the space between thoughts, in the pause between breaths, in the place where the heart rests and the mind grows still. It does not announce itself. It does not argue or insist. It simply waits, patient as water, clear as open sky.",
} as Record<number, string>);
